{"cursor":"43387","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Statistical mechanics' or 'statistical thermodynamics' The terms\nstatistical mechanics and statistical thermodynamics are used interchangeably.\n[[Statistical physics]] is a broader term which includes statistical mechanics,\nbut is sometimes also used as a synonym for statistical mechanics is a\nbranch of physics that applies probability theory, which contains mathematical\ntools for dealing with large populations, to the study of the thermodynamic\nbehavior of systems composed of a large number of particles. Statistical\nmechanics provides a framework for relating the microscopic properties of\nindividual atoms and molecules to the macroscopic bulk properties of materials\nthat can be observed in everyday life, thereby explaining thermodynamics as a\nresult of the classical and quantum-mechanical descriptions of statistics and\nmechanics at the microscopic level.\n\nStatistical mechanics provides a molecular-level interpretation of macroscopic\nthermodynamic quantities such as work, heat, free energy, and entropy. It\nenables the thermodynamic properties of bulk materials to be related to the\nspectroscopic data of individual molecules. This ability to make macroscopic\npredictions based on microscopic properties is the main advantage of statistical\nmechanics over classical thermodynamics. Both theories are governed by the\nsecond law of thermodynamics through the medium of entropy. However, entropy in\nthermodynamics can only be known empirically, whereas in statistical mechanics,\nit is a function of the distribution of the system on its micro-states.\n\nStatistical mechanics was initiated in 1870 with the work of Austrian physicist\nLudwig Boltzmann, much of which was collectively published in Boltzmann's 1896\nLectures on Gas Theory. (section 1.2) Boltzmann's original papers on\nthe statistical interpretation of thermodynamics, the H-theorem, transport\ntheory, thermal equilibrium, the equation of state of gases, and similar\nsubjects, occupy about 2,000 pages in the proceedings of the Vienna Academy and\nother societies. The term \"statistical thermodynamics\" was proposed for use by\nthe American thermodynamicist and physical chemist J. Willard Gibbs in 1902.\nAccording to Gibbs, the term \"statistical\", in the context of mechanics, i.e.\nstatistical mechanics, was first used by the Scottish physicist James Clerk\nMaxwell in 1871. \"Probabilistic mechanics\" might today seem a more appropriate\nterm, but \"statistical mechanics\" is firmly entrenched.\n","linknr":741,"url":"Statistical_mechanics","recorded":1362509646,"links":57,"instances":["hamiltonian","physics","mathematical_physics","statistical_mechanics","letter","statistical_mechanics","thermodynamics","physics_and_chemistry","physicist"],"pdf":["http://farside.ph.utexas.edu/teaching/sm1/statmech.pdf"],"categories":["Concepts in physics","Physics","Statistical mechanics|*","Thermodynamics"],"headings":["Overview","Fundamentals","History","Fundamental postulate","Statistical ensembles","Random walks","Classical thermodynamics vs. statistical thermodynamics","Related","See also","Notes","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Increasing_disorder.svg/220px-Increasing_disorder.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Office-book.svg/16px-Office-book.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/a/4/aa4552efbf56be9021b499898cdc48f7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/9/4/394107b328aef817421898ee1f19cb3e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/8/e/a8e8e7200ddb2d742070fe3f7303cb9c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/3/e/03e3b2c2f97a00773bdc8632ffa169bc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/9/d/b9d99db8626de63193c7fe96273a6cae.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/6/8/a6809df63fe0feb3e70f292e4de6c840.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/a/0/fa0128c219122d7d4ee387586a2f2c86.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/3/8/538